   <abstract>Paul Hindemith wrote his three organ sonatas during the period in organbuilding known as the Organ Reform Movement, which idealized Baroque organs and sought to create new instruments which reflected these Baroque ideals. In the USA in particular, there was a stark contrast between the American symphonic organs and these neoclassical organs. These contrasting organ types, each with their own unique capabilities, present a performer with two contrasting approaches to the performance of Hindemith's organ sonatas: the orchestral approach and the neoclassical approach. Though organ music already presents problems of interpretation, such as a lack of knowledge of the intended instrument, and a lack of registration or one which exceeds the capabilities of one's given instrument, Hindemith's own flawed understanding of the organ presents even further problems and ambiguities. The best evidence to turn to for answers to these problems are Hindemith's own writings, principally his books Johann Sebastian Bach: Heritage and Obligation (1952), A Composer's World (1952), and Traditional Harmony Book II (1953), as well as accounts from two of his students, Robert Noehren and Hagop Frank Bozyan, regarding what Hindemith expected from their performance of the sonatas. As for any ambiguities in Hindemith's scores which cannot be explained according to these sources, such as redundant, contradictory, or otherwise unclear information, the performer must exercise good judgment and deductive reasoning to arrive at a reasonable and musical solution.</abstract>
